  "method": [
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Peel and cut the onions in half across the belly, leaving the top and tail attached.\nPeel the garlic cloves and roughly chop the ginger."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Preheat the oven to 220°C."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Unpack the pork leg joint and pat dry with paper towels. Preheat your biggest\npan over a high heat and add a splash of olive oil. Colour the pork on all sides\nbut the skin. Work your way around methodically, don’t rush! Once the pork is\nthoroughly browned, set aside."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Add the onions cut-side down and cook until very caramelised. Chuck in the\nwhole garlic cloves and the ginger. Cook until fragrant, a couple of mins, then\npeel in the zest of 3 oranges in big strips. Add the juice and the beer plus 400ml\nof water. Chuck in the rosemary, bay and sugar and stir. Season with a little salt\nand pepper, nestle the pork back into the liquid, skin-side up, so most of the\nmeat is submerged (if you need to top up with water, that’s fine) and chuck in\nthe oven for 30-40 mins."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Once the skin has started to crackle and blister, reduce the heat to 140°C and\ncook for a further 4-5 hours. Once completely tender and the skin is super\ncrispy, transfer the pork and braised onions and garlic to a serving platter, finish\nwith fresh orange zest. Skim the fat off the sauce, reduce a little and serve\nalongside."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Slice the white onion very thin, add fresh orange segments and roughly torn\ncoriander stalks ‘n all. Toss with olive oil and serve over top."
    }
  ],
